QDs were used along with anti-E2-DNA aptamers (labeled with a fluorescent molecule) for the determination of E2 in various concentrations (Fig. 3.9
                        ). Under a high E2 concentration, a lower fluorescence signal response was obtained, since fewer fluorescence-labeled DNA aptamers were bound to the surface of the QDs (fluorescent aptamers prefer to bind to E2 present in the solution). The linear concentration range of the sensor was 0.82–20.5nM with a detection limit of 0.22nM. Moreover, the system showed great stability when stored at 4°C for 45 days, presenting an average reduction in signal response of 10% at most (Long et al., 2014). Another sensitive aptasensor was developed using CdTe QDs and a ruthenium (Ru) complex for the determination of E2 (Fig. 3.10
                        ). The Ru complex, responsible for quenching the fluorescence of QDs, preferably binds to the aptamer, leading to QD fluorescence. On the other hand, under the presence of E2, the bond between the Ru complex and the aptamer does not occur, resulting in fluorescence quenching. The linear range of the sensor was 0.08–0.4μM, with adetection limit of 37nM, and the system was also able to provide qualitative determination by the naked eye (Huang et al., 2016).
